Hyperparameter selection

Data-driven hyperparameter selection [MaxEnt]

Proper hyperparameter selection allows to develop model with higher potential for transferability.

# load a presence dataset of a Mediterranean coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
oxygen <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/DissolvedMolecularOxygen Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")
productivity <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")

# stack and rename layers
envConditionsPresent <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, oxygen, productivity)
names(envConditionsPresent) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "oxygen", "productivity")
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envConditionsPresent, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envConditionsPresent)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset with threshold feature and no regularization
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, fc = "t", folds = NULL)
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "tempMin", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 1, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "tempMin", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 5, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "tempMin", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# fit a Maxent model with threshold feature and different regularization
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, reg = 25, fc = "t", folds = NULL)

# inspect the effect of one variable
plotResponse(model, var = "tempMin", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# prepare data splitting for cross-validation
folds <- getBlocks(modelData)
# train a model with threshold feature
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = folds, fc = "t")

# given a set of possible hyperparameter values (regularization)
h <- list(reg = seq(1, 25, 1))
# train models with all the possible combinations of hyperparameters
exp1 <- gridSearch(model, hypers = h, metric = "auc")
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

plot(exp1)

head(exp1@results)

## 5  t   5 0.9971717 0.9944668 0.002704907

# get the best hyperparameter value and fit a model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = folds, fc = "t", reg = 10)
plotResponse(model, var = "tempMin", type = "logistic", color = "Black")

Data-driven hyperparameter selection [BRT]

# load a presence dataset of a Mediterranean coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
oxygen <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/DissolvedMolecularOxygen Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")
productivity <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")

# stack and rename layers
envConditionsPresent <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, oxygen, productivity)
names(envConditionsPresent) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "oxygen", "productivity")
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

Data-driven hyperparameter selection [BRT]

# generate pseudo absences
absences <- pseudoAbsences(envConditionsPresent, presences, n = 1000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, absences, envConditionsPresent)

# prepare data splitting for cross-validation
folds <- getBlocks(modelData)

# train a BRT model
model <- train("BRT", modelData, folds = folds)

# given a set of possible hyperparameter values (interaction.depth or tree complexity)
h <- list(interaction.depth = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5))

# train models with all the possible combinations of hyperparameters
exp1 <- gridSearch(model, hypers = h, metric = "auc")
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

plot(exp1)

# get the best hyperparameter value and fit a BRT model to the dataset
model <- train("BRT", modelData, interaction.depth = 2, folds = folds)
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

Variable selection

Data-driven variable selection

In cases which a model has some environmental variables ranked with very low contribution and one may want to remove them in order to reduce the complexity of the model.

# determine relative variable contribution
viModel <- varImp(model, permut = 5)
plotVarImp(viModel)

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

getAUC(model, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9950797
# reduce model complexity by dropping one variable at a time then remove all variables that
# have a permutation importance lower than 5%.
reducedModel <- reduceVar(model, th = 5, metric = "auc", permut = 5)

# determine relative variable contribution and performance as AUC of the reduced model
viModel <- varImp(reducedModel, permut = 5)
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

plotVarImp(viModel)

getAUC(model, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9950797
getAUC(reducedModel, test = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9918436

Monotonicity

Monotonicity constrains in ecological modelling

# load a presence dataset of a Mediterranean coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
oxygen <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/DissolvedMolecularOxygen Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")
productivity <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")

# stack and rename layers
envConditionsPresent <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, oxygen, productivity)
names(envConditionsPresent) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "oxygen", "productivity")
S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# generate pseudo absences
absences <- pseudoAbsences(envConditionsPresent, presences, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, absences, envConditionsPresent)

# fit a BRT model to the dataset
model <- train("BRT", modelData, folds = NULL)

plotResponse(model, var = "tempMax", color = "Black")

S6 // Data-driven hyperparameter and variable selection

# prepare a dataset of monotonicity constrains

# 0 for no monotonicity effect, -1 for negative effect and +1 for positive effect

monotonicity <- data.frame(tempMin = +1, tempMax = -1, oxygen = +1, productivity = +1)
head(monotonicity)
##   tempMin tempMax oxygen productivity
## 1       1      -1      1            1

# fit a BRT model to the dataset with monotonicity constrains
